SIMPLE: ornament
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: ornament
<hw>or"na*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>ornement</ets>, F. <ets>ornement</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>ornamentum</ets>, fr. <ets>ornare</ets> to adorn.]</ety> <def>That
which embellishes or adorns; that which adds grace or beauty;
embellishment; decoration; adornment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>ornament</qex> of a meek and quiet spirit.</q> <rj><qau>1
Pet. iii. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like that long-buried body of the king⟦br⟧
Found lying with his urns and <qex>ornaments</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>ornament</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: ornament
<hw>or"na*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Ornamented</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ornamenting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To adorn; to deck; to
embellish; to beautify; <as>as, to <ex>ornament</ex> a room, or a
city</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Adorn</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>ornamental</ent>⟦br⟧
